### After trauma, protests resume

In the aftermath of the RSF attack, several military officers were arrested
and the TMC launched an investigation, [admitting wrong-
doing](https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/14/sudan-military-admits-
abuses-committed-in-khartoum-attack?CMP=share_btn_tw), according to The
Guardian:

> Sudan‚Äôs military rulers admitted that security forces had committed abuses
> during the attack on the camp. They appear to have been spontaneous as
> frustration grows after opposition leaders called off a general strike
> intended to force the generals to agree a transition to civilian rule.

But protesters are wary of the TMC's gestures of reconciliation to resume
talks, saying that trust with the TMC is broken after they [abused their
power](https://www.africanews.com/2019/06/13/sudan-s-president-bashir-steps-
down-govt-sources/) in the June 3 dispersal. Instead, protesters have demanded
an [independent investigation](https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sudan-
politics/distrust-between-sudanese-parties-makes-direct-talks-impossible-us-
official-idUSKCN1TF2D2) into the massacre.

Award-winning Sudanese filmmaker, Hajooj Kuka ([‚ÄúBeats of the
Antonov‚Äù](https://www.pbs.org/pov/beatsoftheantonov/)), took part in the sit-
in and was also wounded. He says [‚Äúthe reports of mass rapes are true and
consistent with what we have been seeing on the ground,‚Äù ](https://city-
press.news24.com/News/if-hes-not-dead-then-finish-him-off-20190608)to City
Press.

The TMC continues to hold onto power, with financial aid from Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates in the amount of [$3
billion.](https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/14/sudan-military-admits-
abuses-committed-in-khartoum-attack?CMP=share_btn_tw)

A [12-day internet
shutdown](https://www.internetsociety.org/news/statements/2019/turn-the-
internet-back-on-in-sudan-and-keep-it-on/) has made it difficult for the
[Sudanese Professionals
Association](https://www.sudaneseprofessionals.org/en/) (SPA) and other
protest coalition members to continue to organize protests on social media,
but protests in Khartoum and the city of Port Sudan continued as of Friday,
June 14, through word-of-mouth and SMS messages. These, too, have been met
with [ammunition and brute force](https://www.huffpost.com/entry/sudan-crisis-
dictator-protests-blackout_n_5d03f7dbe4b0304a120f78e0).

#### Read more: [Netizen Report: Amid demonstrations for democracy, Sudanese
civilians face military violence ‚Äî and internet shutdowns
](https://advox.globalvoices.org/2019/06/14/netizen-report-amid-
demonstrations-for-democracy-sudanese-civilians-face-military-violence-and-
internet-shutdowns/ "Netizen Report: Amid demonstrations for democracy,
Sudanese civilians face military violence ‚Äî and internet shutdowns")

The hashtag #IAmTheSudanRevolution, endorsed by the SPA ‚Äî a leading voice in
the protests whose members have stood at the frontlines of negotiations ‚Äî is
also trending:

>
> [#IAmTheSudanRevolution](https://twitter.com/hashtag/IAmTheSudanRevolution?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> because my people cannot die in vain, cannot die in silence under an
> internet blackout. because peaceful protest was met with a massacre. because
> my people deserve dignity, deserve freedom, deserve for the world to know us
> and our fight
>
> ‚Äî Safia Elhillo (@mafiasafia) [June 6,
> 2019](https://twitter.com/mafiasafia/status/1136656600175960064?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

[BBC's Africa editor, Fergal Keane,](https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-
africa-48642546/sudan-protest-witnesses-saw-death-in-all-its-forms)
interviewed eyewitnesses who describe how the massacre had one aim: ‚Äúto break
the revolution by traumatizing.‚Äù

The RSF's violence exhausted and nearly broke the spirit of protesters ‚Äî which
makes the impact of social media campaigns such as #BlueForSudan particularly
important for building bridges between protesters and the rest of the world.

